Assignment: Capstone project proposal - Creating Two Bioinformatics pipelines to analyze Cut&Run data and RNA-seq data

Proposal: We are aiming to analyze the effect of Transcription factors in antiviral and autoimmune environments. There are two transcription factors (TF) we will target in this analysis which are ELF1 and IRF1. The two goals we are aiming for is one, to characterize dynamic targets of antiviral transcription factors mentioned during the inflammatory responses. Two, how does the TF lessen DNA damage response in cells. In the setting of Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), we would like to discover which genes are differentially expressed as a response to the different states, an antiviral state with influenza (IAV), or DNA damage state with bleomycin (BLEO) as compared to the normal state (Mock). These are our three conditions when looking at the influence the selected TFâs play in regulation of interferon stimulated genes (ISG). There is a gene, SYNGR1, which is involved in causing SLE in patients when it acquires a Single Nucleotide Polymorphism (SNP). When this SNP is observed, it allows for the binding of the ELF1 TF which increases the expression of this gene. The knowledge of this mechanism influences us to look at other such cases where TFs are given access to these regions causing increased expression of other genes, which may or may not play a role in SLE. This is why in the Cut&Run pipeline I would be discovering motif sequences in the regions the peaks are called. Also, finding genes immediately downstream of each peak called, will allow us to see which genes are connected in this mechanism.

My Role:

As the sole bioinformatics team member, I am given two sets of data. 1) Cut&Run PE50 reads, ELF1 Knockdown and Control. Three conditions mock, IAV, Bleo

  1. RNA-seq PE50 reads, ELF1 Knockdown and Control. Three conditions mock, IAV, Bleo

Goal: Create a pipeline that takes the cut&run reads and eventually discover genes immediately downstream of each peak, and also discover Motifs. This will be the first pipeline.

Create a second pipeline that takes the RNA-seq reads and create a count table where I can used Deseq2 to find differentially expressed genes

Finally the ultimate goal is to find the genes that appear both in the peaks downstream in the cut&run pipeline, and the differentially expressed genes from the RNA-seq pipeline. Those genes that appear in both will then be our targed genes to feed into the outpredict ML model developed by Jacopo lab. I will also be trained on using outpredict.

Since publically available data is hard to use with the ML training, we have aquired our own data and will have to preprocess and pipeline it for use in the gene regulatory network interface.

This pipeline will allow others to reproduce the data.

Literature Review

Literature Review for capstone project

There are many tools I would like to use when creating the pipeline for analyzing SLE data. Here I will provide a brief explanation of the tools used and also references. First to create the pipeline I need to use a workflow system. Workflow systems allow for not only reproducibility but also provides a space where an entire pipeline can exist in one location. This is how interoperability between tools can be fully realized, in the sense that the output from one tool is seamlessly used as the input for another tool. In a this paper and many others like it, you can get a comparison of many workflow management systems1. There are many tools mentioned here as candidates and that list consists of: Snakemake, cwltool, Toil, and Nextflow. Two tools I have known about through word of mouth, were snakemake and nextflow1. So, for this project I needed to do research on both and choose the workflow management system that I would like to learn and implement, my workflow management system of choice is Nextflow. In addition to reproducibility, Nextflow allows for the resumption of jobs by cashing previous processes that ran and have not been changed. It also allows for the use of containers/ singularities which can be used on local machines or the HPC respectively2. The ease of developing pipelines is one of the main reasons to use nextflow. It is based on groovy, a programming language that is not hard to learn and implement, yet you can use the languages you like such as unix, python, and R to run the bioinformatics tools and software as you would otherwise. Groovy is only used to link processes together through channels, and once you learn how to do that, you know how to create a Nextflow pipeline.

Cut&Run Pipeline Now, for the tools I used in Nextflow. Like I mentioned you can use the same programming language you love to implement the tools themselves in each process in nextflow. This project consists of Cut&Run data, so I need bioinformatics tools that can analyze essentially Chip-seq data. First tool used in the pipeline is fastp. This tool allows for the preprocessing of the pair end 50 (PE50) reads provided to me3. I can trim reads and ensure they pass the qc metrics for downstream analysis. Ultimately I decided against trimming any of the reads, this will avoid any loss of important data. Multiqc and fastqc are other tools that helps me combine all the data produced by fastp so I can ensure all the data has passed the qc metrics at once4. The next tool would be using BWA aln to align the preprocessed reads to the human reference genome. This aligner is chosen because Cut&Run data is essentially DNA based data, which looks at the protein-DNA interaction to discover epigenetic altercations, and needs a DNA aligner to align the reads properly as you can see in this paper 5. For further explanation on the settings and options I used with BWA-aln please see the official vignette. Next tool used is samtools, this is to convert the sam produced by the alignment to a bam file, sort and then index that bam file to be used in further downstream analysis tools6. The last tool in this pipeline to analyze Cut&Run data is homer and one of the most important. HOMER is a suite of tools that can call peaks, find genes downstream of the peaks, and also find transcription factor motifs7. HOMER is the most important tool used in this data analysis pipeline. Recently, Cut&Run has gained in popularity due to the low number of cells needed to achieve a high signal to noise ratio versus ChIP-Seq. Also due to the lowering costs of producing Cut&Run data more experiments are including replicates. Replicates are subsequent runs of an experiment within the same condition. For example, we have three conditions, Mock, IAV, and Bleomycin. Each condition consists of Knockdown experiments and Control experiments. Instead of only having one knockdown and one control sample, we have 6 knockdown and 6 control samples, which pair with each other respectively, in each of the three conditions. This is a relatively new addition because of the low costs to conduct these experiments as compared to earlier years when ChIP-Seq and Cut&Run were novel. HOMER has a tool, amongst its suite of tools, that can find differentially expressed peaks between all the replicates in each condition. This is one of the many new tools that exists now, which came about because of the increasing use of replicates by scientists. You can find a few more tool other than HOMER, that can find differential peaks in the journal comparing the results and accuracy of 14 different tools8. The command in HOMER that does this comparison between replicates is âgetDifferentialPeaksReplicates.plâ. You can find more about how I used this command in my pipeline by referring to the appendix section for the Cut&Run pipeline, or looking on my Github repository that contains my Cut&Run pipeline files and look for the HOMER file. The purpose of the Cut&Run pipeline is to analyze transcription factors and their influence on gene expression when dysregulated. This dysregulation comes from possible autoinflammatory, antiviral, or even DNA damage that may occur in a person thus causing SLE. So we need to know more about SLE in humans and the emergence conditions such as arthritis, rashes, and renal failure9.

RNA-Seq Pipeline

Methodology

I will be using Nextflow to create two pipelines. The first pipeline is to analyze Cut&Run PE50 reads, and the second pipeline is to analyze RNA-seq PE50 reads. The tools used in the Cut&Run pipeline are fastp, fastqc, multiqc, bwa aln, samtools, homer, and ChIC R package. I mentioned the reason for choosing these tools in the literature review of them above. The tools used in the RNA-seq pipeline are fastp, fastqc, multiqc, STAR, featureCounts, and DEseq2. The featureCounts is the quantification step of the pipeline, in which the output will be used in DEseq2 to then find differential expressed genes. After both pipelines are complete we will have annotated peaks, from the Cut&Run pipeline, which consists of genes that are found downstream of the peaks and we will have differential expressed genes from the RNA-seq pipeline. The goal is to imagine a venn diagram, where the intersection of these two pipelines are showing genes that are found in both. The genes found downstream of peaks and are also differentially expressed will be our target genes for further analysis and in training of the machine learning model Outpredict.

RNA-Seq Pipeline

Many of the initial tools used in the Cut&Run pipeline were used here and I will list those such tools instead of going into greater detail. FASTP, FASTQC, Samtools, Multiqc were all used in the preprocessing of the fastq files for the RNA-Seq pipeline. One tool that differs in the preprocessing stages of the pipeline is the use of STAR. STAR is an aligner that is splice aware, this means that it understands the reads are coming from exons and if we have to align to a reference genome, there will be introns that the RNA reads may have spanned before the introns were spliced out10. You can see the parameters of STAR in my pipeline when implemented in the appendix. The process in the RNA-Seq pipeline that uses STAR will be named âstarâ (when generating the genome to use) and âstar_alignâ (when using STAR to align the fastq reads to the genome that was generated in the previous step). Once all the initial standard preprocessing is complete, we get back bam files for each replicate. The next part of the pipeline involves using R language and the packages featurecounts, DESeq2, EnhancedVolcano. To seamlessly use R in nextflow without having to download packages every time we run the process, and to ensure reproducibility, I decided to create a container to store the version of R and the packages/dependencies I need to complete the pipeline. Singularity is the tool used to create containers for nextflow pipelines used on the HPC due to compatibility requirements11. You can find a detailed explanation on how I created my singularity container for R on my github repository for the RNA-Seq pipeline. Next, I use featurecounts, an R package for quantification of the genes. This will essentially give me the counts for each gene in the replicates. The counts will then be input in to DESeq2 to get differentially expressed genes. I created an R script that does both steps and can also be found in the RNA-seq repository. This R script is called by the process âr_featurecountsâ, you can find it in the appendix or the RNA-Seq repository.

Cut&Run Pipeline

This is nextflow code I wrote to make my pipeline. I runs on the language Groovy. In nextflow there are processes, which are the individual sections that are excuted, and channels, which are the ways by which you can input or output data from one process to another process. There are also parameters that help store data that can be placed in a channel.

You can tell where each process is by the syntax: process {}

In each process, there is a input and output section, also a script section where the tools that will be excuted are located. The script section is between three triple qoutes above and below the script I want to run.

I am able to place the output of each script into a channel to be used in another process. Since I am using the DSL2 version of nextflow, the syntax looks like this:

output: path â${pair_id}_R1.filt.fq.gzâ, emit: fastp_out_f

For example, I declared this is the output section using âoutput:â. Then I took the file name that should have been generated by the script section of this process and put it into a channel called âfastp_out_fâ, using the âemit:â option.

This nextflow pipeline only outputs bam files and then I wrote a separate script to input the bam files into HOMER, a suite of tools, that can call peaks, annotate the peaks, and discover modifs.

In the future I will add another process to the nextflow pipeline that will use HOMER in the script section. For now it isnt part of my pipeline in nextflow. I use a bash script to call my nextflow pipeline then once the pipeline finishes, I then call my HOMER script in the same bash script.

Thereâs a bit of a learning curve when creating channels, and at the time I wasnât sure how to get the bam file into pairs so I can make the HOMER process in my nextflow pipeline.

I will add the HOMER script under the pipeline script. Then I will add the config file and the bash script used to run everything on the HPC.

Results for RNA-seq pipeline

From the data above with 7 genes, it looks like the THUMPD3-AS1 gene is up regulated. This looks good because this gene is part of the long non-coding RNA class (lncRNA), and according to the article, it enhances the proliferation and inflammatory response of chondrocytes in osteoarthritis9. This is important to us because in Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), one of the emergent conditions a person can experience is arthritis. Two other symptoms of SLE are renal failure, and rashes. So, two of the genes so far are expected, ELF1, THUMPD3-AS1. Another thing to note is that the gene THUMPD3-AS1 is increasing in expression from control to knockdown. Since the experimental design in DESeq2 is knockdown_vs_control, this means that as ELF1 is removed this gene is expressed more. This means the lack of an ELF1 transcription factor allows THUMPD3-AS1 to be expressed more and that ELF1 must regulate this gene.

One gene seen in the ELF1 Mock rna-seq condition is ITGAX. This gene contributes to the progression of Atherosclerosis10. Atherosclerosis is most prevalent in people with arthritis, so this gene is important to us since a symptom of SLE is arthritis.

I provided Venn diagrams below of the three conditions, showing how many genes overlap between the different samples. To make it easier for the wet lab team to validate the differentially expressed genes, I took the three experiment conditions and created a Venn Diagram to elucidate which genes are unique to each condition, which genes appear in all three, and which genes are in any two conditions.

HOMER script

The first step is to make tag directories with the bam files. This allows for more flexibility when using other tools part of HOMER. To make the tag directories you need to use the command âmakeTagDirectoryâ, then add the name of the tag directory you wish to create and finally the bam file that will be used to create the data that populates that directory. You can refer to the âHOMER script codeâ in the appendix to see how this is done. I essentially created three tag directories. One for the knockdown, control and bg (background bam IgG). Next, I use the âfindPeaksâ tool/ command, which calls the peaks using the knockdown tag directory and the IgG tag directory as the background genomic data. I call find peaks a second time which uses the control tag directory and the IgG tag directory. Lastly, I call the find peaks command a third time but only with the bg tag directories. The âfindPeaksâ command will then use a parameter â-styleâ and the option âfactorâ, to specify that the cut&run data we are using to find peaks are from transcription factor proteins. This will ensure that any algorithms the program uses will find narrow peaks that are significant instead of looking for broad peaks. Narrow peaks are generally produced by transcription factors. The âfindPeaksâ command will then produce a peak file that we can name using the â-oâ parameter. The next step is to convert the files I named with a suffix of âpeak.txtâ to bed files. To do this, I used the HOMER command âpos2bed.plâ. The first input after listing the command is to put the full name of the peak file generated in the previous step then use the unix command â>â to put the STDOUT into a new file with a suffix in the name â_peakfile.bedâ. Next, I define the reference genome I want to use and store it in a variable called ârefâ. The reference genome is found from the GENCODE website: https://www.gencodegenes.org/human/ . Also I do the same for the gtf file, also found from the gencode website. The reference genome is under the FASTA section and is the CRCH38 primary assembly version and this can be seen clearly in the code. However, the gtf file isnât so clear, because I did some altercations to it and then called the new gtf file âtest_this.gtfâ. The GTF file I used from gencode is under the GTF/GFF3 files section, and I chose the GTF âBasic gene annotationâ since it is the main annotation file for most users. Going from this GTF file to the âtest_this.gtfâ file all I did was grep the lines in the downloaded GTF file that had exon in them, then added those lines to the new file called âtest_this.gtfâ. This ensures that problems with the annotate peaks step are avoided.
After doing this, it allows me to annotate the peaks, but I donât do that step next in my script. I first call motifs using âfindMotifsGenome.plâ, then I annotate the peaks using âannotatePeaks.plâ. The order doesnât matter.

# THIS IS A TEST TO USE THE IgG AS THE CONTROL INSTEAD OF THE CONTROL. I WILL DO THIS TWICE ALSO
# ONCE FOR KNOCKDOWN WITH IGG AND THEN WITH CONTROL AND IGG

#rm kd_bam.txt ctr_bam.txt bg_region.txt kd_ctr_bg_bam.txt

line="$(less "$pair_bams" | head -n ${SLURM_ARRAY_TASK_ID} | tail -n 1)"

module load homer/4.11

makeTagDirectory $bam_kd'_tag_dir/' $bam_kd -tbp 1
makeTagDirectory $bam_ctr'_tag_dir/' $bam_ctr -tbp 1

Homer script to get differential peaks

Since we have 6 replicates of knockdown and 6 of control for each condition, I need to find differential peaks between them to get the peaks that are only significant. Once I find the differential peaks I will annotate those peaks and get genes downstream that are more significant than the genes found by doing this for each replicate individually.

This part is still a work in progress. So far this code gives back 43 differential peaks for the bleomycin condition, 5 for the IAV condition, and 0 for the Mock condition. One possiblilty is that trying to find differential peaks with 6 replicates is too much. I may try only using 3 replicates in the future. Next option is to look at IDR (irreproducible discovery rate) which is the threshold that is supposed to work when looking for differential peaks with many replicates in a ChIP-seq experiment or Cut&Run experiment.

Pipeline for RNA-seq data

The below code is nextflow code that is the pipeline for the RNA-seq data I am working with. This code does not run in this jupyter notebook because I am using the R kernel currently and also because nextflow uses groovy language.

This pipeline uses many processes just like the Cut&Run pipeline above. Some important differences are as follows. I use STAR to align the pair end reads to a reference genome. STAR is a splice aware aligner. This is done using unix code within the script section of the process. Many of the other processes use unix in the script section also.

There is a process that uses R language and that is how I run the tools featureCounts, which creates a quantification file from the bam files produced. Then the R script I created uses DESeq2 to find differentially expressed genes by using the output files created from the featureCounts tool.

To be able to use R in the nextflow process I needed to create a container that contains the R language and also I needed to add R packages that I want to use that are not originally part of R. This allows me to have all the required tools in one place to be used in the script section of the R process that I named âr_featurecountsâ.

The container was created using singularity, which is a tool that allows docker containers to be compatable with the HPC.

The benefit of containers is that it allows for reproducibility. This is because the version of the tool I put into the container cannot be changed or updated. Also only packages that are added upon creation of the container are able to be used. Which means if I want to use a new R package I will not be able to download it while in R, I would have to add it to the singularity definition file before the container is created.

Below the nextflow pipeline, I will have a section where I paste the commands I used to create this container.

Then below that, you will be able to find the actual commands that I ran in this jupyter notebook. These commands are copied and pasted from the Rscript I created, which is called in the nextflow process âr_featurecountsâ.

Singularity Definition file (.def)

The r_dev_test.def file is a singularity definition file that contains the instructions for building a singularity container image. When on the HPC you will need only one module to load. That is the singularityCE module. The version I have available to me is singularity-ce/3.11.0 Once this is loaded we will build a .sif file using the remote method, since we probably do not have root access on the HPC. First we may have to login to singularity

singularity remote login You will need to go to the singularity website, create an account and login then generate an access key in the top right. Then copy and paste that access key into the terminal as a way to remote login.

Next we can build finally

singularity build âremote .sif r_dev_test.def This will create the .sif file with the name of your choice. And now the container can be specified in the nextflow config file and placed in the process that will use this container.

To check if the container works as intended you can just do the following

singularity run .sif This should open R in the command line, and now you can load the three packages we want to use

library(DESeq2) library(Rsubread) library(EnhancedVolcano) In the nextflow pipeline, I have a process that calls the .R file that contains the R commands I want to use. Once this script runs sussessfully in nextflow, a work directory will be created that does not contain any files. If you update the .R file and add new code or change anything, you will need to go into the slurm script and find the directory where the process r_featurecounts calls the .R script and then delete that directory only. This way the nextflow -resume command will not think the process is still cashed. Ex how to delete that directory:

rm work/de/111b213d38af9696476b48cc3cee04/ This is the directory for me that contains that âcashedâ output, even though it is empty. Now you can run the pipeline again with the updated commands in the .R file.

Using Microsoft Bing (powered by gpt4) to explain why the volcano plots look different and which I should choose

My question:

when should I use padj or pvalue when creating an enhancedvolcano plot in r, of my differentially expressed genes?

Bingâs answer:

In an EnhancedVolcano plot, the x axis typically represents the log2 fold change between two conditions, while the y axis represents the statistical significance of the change, usually measured by the negative log10 of the p-value or adjusted p-value (padj).

The choice between using p-value or adjusted p-value (padj) depends on the specific analysis youâre performing and the level of stringency you want to apply when controlling for false positives. In general, when performing multiple hypothesis tests, itâs common to use an adjusted p-value to control the false discovery rate. This is because, when performing multiple tests, the probability of observing a significant result by chance alone increases.

In the context of differential gene expression analysis, if youâre comparing the expression levels of many genes between two conditions, itâs common to use an adjusted p-value (padj) to control for multiple testing. This helps to reduce the number of false positives and increase the reliability of your results.

In summary, if youâre performing multiple hypothesis tests and want to control for false positives, itâs generally a good idea to use an adjusted p-value (padj) when creating an EnhancedVolcano plot. However, the specific choice depends on your analysis and the level of stringency you want to apply. I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any further questions.

My Conclusion:

I think since we want to ultimately compare the differentially expressed genes from the RNA-seq experiment with the ones found downstream of the peaks in the Cut&Run experiment, it would be best to look at the genes returned by looking at the p-value. This is because we get a wider selection of genes and we will be able to cross check if they are false positives by the non existance of any of them found in the downstream Cut&Run analysis. Like wise, if the genes are seen in both that would mean they are true positives. Thus, we will perform our own check of determining if a gene is false positive or true positive.

# just put all gene names in one file
all_gene_names = NULL
#all_gene_names = append(mock_de_peaks$Gene.Name, all_gene_names)

all_gene_names = c(mock_de_peaks$Gene.Name, iav_de_peaks$Gene.Name, bleo_de_peaks$Gene.Name)
length(all_gene_names)

# now for each condition and column that contains only the gene names,
# i will check to see if that name exists in a file then append it if it does not

unique_gene_names =NULL

for (x in c(1:length(all_gene_names)) ) {
    if(! all_gene_names[x] %in% unique_gene_names) unique_gene_names = append(all_gene_names[x], unique_gene_names)
}

# this shows us that there is some overlapping genes but not many
length(unique_gene_names)

# now we create a df that takes boolean values to construct the venn diagram

cutrun_venn_data = data.frame(genes = unique_gene_names, Mock =NA, IAV = NA, Bleo = NA)

head(cutrun_venn_data, 10)

# now to populate the df with boolean values

for (x in c(1:length(cutrun_venn_data[,1]))){
    if(cutrun_venn_data[x,1] %in% mock_de_peaks$Gene.Name) cutrun_venn_data[x,2] = TRUE else(cutrun_venn_data[x,2] = FALSE)
    
    if(cutrun_venn_data[x,1] %in% iav_de_peaks$Gene.Name) cutrun_venn_data[x,3] = TRUE else(cutrun_venn_data[x,3] = FALSE)
    
    if(cutrun_venn_data[x,1] %in% bleo_de_peaks$Gene.Name) cutrun_venn_data[x,4] = TRUE else(cutrun_venn_data[x,4] = FALSE)
}
